description: From Middle English overmacchen, equivalent to over- +‎ match.

entries.meaning: A match in which one opponent is greatly superior to the other.
examples: […]  we can increase the velocity of that force, so as to make it an overmatch for its antagonist.

entries.meaning: An opponent who is more than a match for another; one who cannot be defeated.

verbs.description: overmatch (third-person singular simple present overmatches, present participle overmatching, simple past and past participle overmatched)

examples: The regular expression overmatched, capturing the entire paragraph instead of the specific sentence.

entries.meaning: To be more than equal to or a match for, to surpass; hence, to conquer, vanquish.
examples: At Lemster, for her Wooll whose Staple doth excell,
And seemes to over-match the golden Phrygian Fell.
